TI  - Loss of TREM2 rescues hyperactivation of microglia, but not lysosomal deficits 
      and neurotoxicity in models of progranulin deficiency.
PG  - e109108
LID - 10.15252/embj.2021109108 [doi]
LID - e109108
AB  - Haploinsufficiency of the progranulin (PGRN)-encoding gene (GRN) causes 
      frontotemporal lobar degeneration (GRN-FTLD) and results in microglial 
      hyperactivation, TREM2 activation, lysosomal dysfunction, and TDP-43 deposition. 
      To understand the contribution of microglial hyperactivation to pathology, we 
      used genetic and pharmacological approaches to suppress TREM2-dependent 
      transition of microglia from a homeostatic to a disease-associated state. Trem2 
      deficiency in Grn KO mice reduced microglia hyperactivation. To explore 
      antibody-mediated pharmacological modulation of TREM2-dependent microglial 
      states, we identified antagonistic TREM2 antibodies. Treatment of macrophages 
      from GRN-FTLD patients with these antibodies led to reduced TREM2 signaling due 
      to its enhanced shedding. Furthermore, TREM2 antibody-treated PGRN-deficient 
      microglia derived from human-induced pluripotent stem cells showed reduced 
      microglial hyperactivation, TREM2 signaling, and phagocytic activity, but 
      lysosomal dysfunction was not rescued. Similarly, lysosomal dysfunction, lipid 
      dysregulation, and glucose hypometabolism of Grn KO mice were not rescued by 
      TREM2 ablation. Synaptic loss and neurofilament light-chain (NfL) levels, a 
      biomarker for neurodegeneration, were further elevated in the Grn/Trem2 KO 
      cerebrospinal fluid (CSF). These findings suggest that TREM2-dependent microglia 
      hyperactivation in models of GRN deficiency does not promote neurotoxicity, but 
      rather neuroprotection.
